Euroopassa vessattomia sellejä on käytössä lähinnä Itä- ja Etelä-Euroopassa sekä Suomessa, mutta ei muissa Pohjoismaissa. Suomessa oli käytössä 736 vessatonta selliä vuonna 2007. "Bad cells" are called cells without toilets, where the prisoner has to defecate, urinate and clean his menstrual flow in a bucket. The smell of the bucket kept under the sink is disturbing when, for example, the prisoner washes his hands or takes drinking water.[1] In cells without toilets for two people, you have to do your needs in front of your roommate[2].

In Europe, cells without toilets are used mainly in Eastern and Southern Europe and in Finland, but not in the other Nordic countries. In Finland, there were 736 cells without toilets in use in 2007. How do you guys say 事実を言うのは悪いことじゃない in English?

A few phrases came across my mind, but I have no idea which one is correct and natural.

>There's nothing wrong with saying the fact
I often see a (pro)noun follow the preposition "with" just like "nothing wrong with him," but is it also correct to place the -ing form after the "with" this way?

>There's nothing wrong in saying the fact
I've seen the preposition "in" come before the -ing form like this many times, but I'm not sure if this works even in this case.

>It's not wrong to say the fact
To the best of my knowledge, I don't think there's anything grammatically wrong with this one, but I feel like this is not quite what I'm trying to express.

Any answers (and corrections if necessary) are welcome!

>>176329935
>事実を言うのは悪いことじゃない
Depends on context. Literally it's something like "[there's] nothing wrong in telling the truth". But, for example, in response to someone thinking you're too blunt you could just say "just telling the truth" or "just saying how it is" (but read the air, as it were, or you might end up sounding like an asshole).

>but is it also correct to place the -ing form after the "with" this way?
"Nothing wrong with [verb]ing" is correct. As for the example sentence, although not wrong it sounds more like you're saying that there is nothing wrong with literally saying "the fact". If you're verbally making a fact known then you're "stating" it.

Once upon a time, in the beautiful island state of Tasmania, lived the largest crustaceans in the world. These giant creatures, called Tasmanian Crustaceans, were a marvel to behold. They had long, spindly legs that could stretch to incredible lengths, and their shells were as hard as steel. They roamed the shores and forests of Tasmania, searching for food and mates.

The locals were fascinated by these magnificent animals and often went out to catch a glimpse of them. Some even ventured into the wild to capture them and bring them back to be studied. Scientists from all over the world came to Tasmania to study these giant crustaceans and learn more about their unique biology.

But as the years went by, the Tasmanian Crustaceans began to disappear. Their numbers dwindled as the forests and oceans were cleared to make way for human development. The locals and scientists were heartbroken by the loss of such a magnificent species.

Determined to save the Tasmanian Crustaceans, a group of conservationists came together to protect their habitat and raise awareness about the importance of preserving these creatures. Thanks to their efforts, the population of Tasmanian Crustaceans began to recover, and soon they were once again thriving in their natural habitat.

The people of Tasmania were overjoyed and they take very good care of the animals and cherish them. The Tasmanian Crustaceans became a symbol of hope and resilience, reminding us that even in the face of adversity, it is possible to save the things we hold dear.

And from that day on, the island was known for not only its natural beauty but also for the giant crustaceans that call it home, and it becomes popular tourist destination for people all over the world who wanted to see the giant crustaceans with their own eyes.

Jeden Tag wache ich um 7 Uhr auf aber in der Regel stehe ich nur dann um 7:15 Uhr auf.
Zum Frühstück esse ich etwa Eier mit einem Glas Orangensaft.
Nach dem Frühstück dusche ich, dann ziehe ich mich an, und schließlich gehe ich zur Arbeit.
Ich beginne die Arbeit um 8 Uhr und ich mache eine Pause zur Mittagessen um halb eins mittags.
Danach kehre ich zur Arbeit zurück.

Als Kind machte meine Familie eine Safarireise in Kenia und es war eine tolle Erfahrung.
Wir haben zehn Löwen, vier Elefanten, verschiedene Zebras und Leoparden sowie noch ein paar Giraffen sehen.
Wir haben die Safari um Mittag herum gemacht und da war es den Tieren zu heiß, die in dem Schatten der Bäume liegen.
Meine Familie und ich wohnen auf dem Land mitten in Deutschland, also was wir normalerweise außerhalb unserem Fenster sehen ist etwas völlig anderes.
Am unseren kleinen Bauernhof haben wir einige Schweine, Hühner, und natürlich auch eine Menge von Schafen, aber wir haben doch nichts wie exotisch als was wir während unserer Safari gesehen haben.

Wir sind, was wir wiederholt tun. Und so ist Vorzüglichkeit dann keine Tat, sondern eine Gewohnheit.
Aus den Aschen wird ein Feuer aufgeweckt, ein Licht von den Schatten springen; erneuert wird die Schneide, die gebrochen wurde. Der ohne Krone wird zum König.
die Moralität geht nicht darum, wie wir uns selbst glücklich machen können, sondern eher darum, wie wir uns selbst des Glückes würdig machen können.
Das Glück liegt an tugendhafter Handlung, und vollendetes Glück liegt an der besten Tat, und zwar Betrachtung.
Wenn wir uns mit einer Sehnsucht, die sich in dieser Welt nicht zufrieden stellen lässt, finden, dann die wahrscheinlichste Lösung dafür ist das wir für eine andere Welt gemacht worden sind.

It sounds like it was basically their equivalent of a made-up name like John Doe, which people would use when they wanted to fly under the radar. But that happened so many times with so many different groups that nearly everyone ended up with the surname Doe.
>The first recorded mention of a person surnamed Nguyen is a 317 CE description of a journey to Giao Châu undertaken by Eastern Jin dynasty (Nhà Tấn, 晉朝) officer Nguyễn Phu [vi] and his family. Many events in Vietnamese history have contributed to the name's prominence. In 1232, after usurping the Lý dynasty, Trần Thủ Độ forced the descendants of the Lý to change their surname to Nguyễn. When Hồ Quý Ly overturned the Trần dynasty, he killed many of their descendants so when the Hồ dynasty collapsed in 1407, many of his descendants changed their surname to Nguyễn in fear of retribution.[citation needed] In 1592, on the collapse of the Mạc dynasty, their descendants changed their surname to Nguyễn. In late 16th century, the Tư Mã clan from Thanh Hóa changed to Nguyễn and settled in Cochinchina.[citation needed] When the Nguyễn dynasty (the descendants of the Nguyễn Lords) took power in 1802, some of the descendants of the Trịnh Lords fearing retribution changed their surname to Nguyễn, while others fled north into China. The Nguyễn dynasty awarded many people the surname Nguyễn during their rule, and many criminals also changed their surname to Nguyễn to avoid prosecution.
